GT Solar Hits Highest in 2 Years on $84.3 Million Silicon Furnace Orders

-- B y   E h r e n   G o o s s e n s
-- 
2011-05-16T15:02:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-16/gt-solar-hits-highest-in-2-years-on-84-3-million-silicon-furnace-orders.html
GT Solar International Inc. (SOLR) , a U.S.
maker of manufacturing equipment for solar wafers, reached a
two-year high after announcing $84.3 million of polysilicon
furnaces sales.  GT Solar rose as much as 77 cents, or 6.8 percent, to
$12.13 in Nasdaq Stock Market trading, its highest since Sept.
19, 2008. The shares were up 42 cents to $11.78 at 10:59 a.m.,
increasing its gain this year to 29 percent.  The company will provide the polysilicon furnaces to
existing customers and to two new China-based clients, Nantong
Zongyi New Material Co. and Inner Mongolia Zhong Huan Solar
Material Co., the Merrimack, New Hampshire-based company said
today in a statement. Polysilicon is used to make solar cells.  GT Solar on May 10 announced contracts to deliver sapphire
crystallization furnaces worth $91 million to Alpha Crystal
Technology Corp. and  Tera Xtal Technology Corp. (4969)  Synthetic
sapphires are used to make energy-saving light-emitting diodes.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ehren Goossens in New York at 
 egoossens1@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
